INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (1,1,'Mr WordPress','','http://wordpress.org/','','2008-11-03 23:12:27','2008-11-04 04:12:27','Hi, this is a comment.<br />To delete a comment, just log in and view the post&#039;s comments. There you will have the option to edit or delete them.',0,'1','','',0,0),(2,3,'zenzimuz','','','','2008-06-05 12:15:00','2008-06-05 17:15:00','What\'s the deal with this month\'s meeting?  Is it happening tonight (Thursday, June 5) or no?  7-7:30 Asgard\'s?',0,'1','','',0,0),(3,6,'Max','','','','2008-09-16 13:11:00','2008-09-16 18:11:00','try lego as a frame, as in the make protocol.<br/>I suggest using cybrsafe as a dye and bluelight (LEDS!) to show the bands. This should be more sensitive than the equipment most labs are using.<br/><br/>Use Borax as the buffer, it is cheaper than TBE and probably easier to get, though I am not completely sure about that.',0,'1','','',0,0),(4,5,'JonathanCline','','','','2008-10-01 03:58:00','2008-10-01 08:58:00','DIY biology is a fascinating realm and just like your group of hackers, I have been interested &amp; studying the field for some time.  Recently I  entered the &quot;mad scientist&quot; Design-a-Biobrick contest to see how actual &quot;DIY&quot; is possible in with synthetic biology (I received an honorable mention).  In the process, I learned more about biology and the wetware involved in genetically modified organisms, and most importantly came to the not-so-startling conclusion:<br/><br/>The hype of synthetic biology and &quot;garage hacking genetics&quot; is greatly exaggerated.<br/><br/>In truth, it does require nearly a graduate degree PLUS a scientific-quality-level research laboratory in order to actually get anything to work.  And even in that case where individuals are so equipped, getting anything to grow, let alone perform and/or activate the &quot;newly designed&quot; biological function, is a very rare feat indeed.<br/><br/>Thus, actual garage hacking of biology is still some number of years off, especially for those outside the technically trained lab tech, graduate level or Ph.D. trained field.  Since right now it&#39;s the end of 2008, that means garage biology labs are still very difficult until 2012 or so.<br/><br/>The best way, today, in my opinion, to get trained on this technology, in order to actually hack and/or build anything, is to probably spend a year towards &quot;professional/graduate biotech lab training&quot; oriented community college classes.  This would include a couple bio classes, an organic chem class, and a bunch of lab training in a real lab.  After 15 to 30 credits worth of training, then it will likely be at least possible to hack something in the garage -- whether or not it grows is up to the DNA and the protocols.',0,'1','','',0,0),(5,5,'Jason Bobe','','','','2008-10-01 12:05:00','2008-10-01 17:05:00','Hi Jonathan -<br/><br/>Thanks for the comment.  There is no doubt that amateur biology is in its early days.  The types of activities/protocols that are practical and accessible at this moment are limited.  <br/><br/>This being said, the challenge today is to identify areas where amateurs can contribute with basic materials, equipment, and training (and this may not be in synbio right now).  Bioinformatics and <a HREF=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/22/science/22fish.html\" REL=\"nofollow\">exploratory biology</a> are two areas where individuals can make contributions today.<br/><br/>RE: classes, I think there may be an opportunity for local training seminars that target individuals who are not professionally inclined, but want to learn technical skills.  Similar to <a HREF=\"http://www.thecrucible.org\" REL=\"nofollow\">The Crucible</a> in Berkeley.<br/><br/><br/><br/>Jason',0,'1','','',0,0),(6,5,'Mackenzie','','','','2008-10-01 19:07:00','2008-10-02 00:07:00','Indeed, one of our primary goals is to build a biology workshop where biotech enthusiasts can do real labwork.  By pooling resources and developing safety and regulatory expertise - with a lot of help and advice from existing labs and institutions - I believe we can set up labs for people who would otherwise not have access to the resources because the are too expensive and difficult to pull together individually.  Additionally, I have confidence that the amazing mix of people that make up the diybio community will rise to the challenge of building a lab on a shoestring and come up with inexpensive and innovative techniques and tools that will enable the typical range of biological operations a traditional academic lab can support.  This will help the development of labs in developing countries, which will help local scientists and entrepreneurs solve local problems.<br/><br/>Additionally, I think our nascent community has the potential to make significant contributions to biological knowledge by investigating non-traditional systems and lifeforms.<br/><br/>Amateur biologists could make significant contributions to biology in general, and synthetic biology in particular, by 1) investigating organisms outside of the handful of already well-characterized model organisms (i.e. P. patens [moss] or halobacteria), and 2) by using existing standardized biological parts, building novel standard biological parts, developing new methods to easily measure biopart activity, and perhaps the lowest-hanging fruit of all: simply characterizing existing parts with existing measurement standards.  Your typical grant-funded synthetic biology grad student may not have the leeway or motivation to do so - but we hobbyists could make a big difference to the toolbox of available standard biological parts by characterizing them.  Almost no one else will.<br/> <br/>So in conclusion, I think amateur biologists could make a big impact immediately by working together in communal workshops.  Next time you are in Boston, you should stop by and try out our facilities :)',0,'1','','',0,0);
